[bkg=bg.pbm][h1]Temperature : ascii scene 30 left?
by Browallia
-----------------------------

ASCII sceners may be seen as outdated by some, but some of us just love it. It's really rare that ASCII artists get credit in an intro. The closest they come are the loading or exit log by pressing LMB (left mouse button). With that said, it's easy to conclude that ASCII artists are part of the community, but the role they play (i.e., being outside the credits in demos and intros) makes them a bit like outsiders.

So. lets. get. on.

THE FOLLOW-UP
I wrote an article in 2019 where I analyzed the ASCII/ANSI scene on Amiga, identifying around 40 active sceners. In this article, I revise this number, providing a decreased estimate of 30 active sceners. For this, I used my own research and our database, where we track nicknames and follow the ASCII/ANSI artists (nukleus.nu/vs). At this point, I should thank aSCIIaRENA (https://www.asciiarena.se/) for confirming the activity of people between 2020 and the beginning of 2024.

What I lack today is the clear connection that exists, but nobody really writes about it. What connection, you may wonder. The intimate relationship between the graffiti scene and ASCII. The mindset of the free spirit, the rough arrogance—an ASCII artist tends to have more attitude than a scener doing graphics, coding, or music, I believe. Remember the origin and the closeness to BBS-driven culture. Boards and the ASCII/ANSI society are more rooted than the average scener.

We started using ASCII in our productions in 1995. We had some great artists doing ASCII, and I was fascinated by the styles. If you ask me, every group should have an ASCII graphic artist; they are valuable, and it's easier to tame a horse than to explain in detail what you want out of the ASCII in a production. But as mentioned above, ASCII groups have formed on the periphery of the scene.





