ACTIVITY
Another thing I wonder is why the feng shui—are collections or remarkable releases so rare these days? Goto80 has been very active recently with collections, but the productive "corona years" were really an exception. After ASCII Arena announced their comeback again (May 2021), there are mainly three larger sources for ASCII today (four if you count IRC): ASCII Arena (web and Discord channel), textmod.es, and the Facebook group "ANSI, ASCII Artists, and BBS Sysops Worldwide." You can, of course, browse into BBSes, and I hope they still get information faster than the web, but I think there is an overlap with productions seen on these three sources. Some may argue that textmod.es has also played out its role today.

Back to ASCII Arena again. Between the beginning of May this year and two months later, on the 8th of July 2024, the two top commenters have only commented on one entry each (Spot and Speed Devil), and there have been five comments in total (from 3899 to 3904). But on the positive side, many new users have arrived—33 new users, in fact (from 601 to 634). But are these new users active ASCII sceners? Well, I don't think so, to be honest. But then more interesting questions arise: when are you considered active, who decides you are active, and which forum determines your activity?

I came to the conclusion that between 2019 and now, 2024, the active ASCII scene on Amiga has decreased from around 40 to 30 sceners. Maybe I'm wrong.


